If you're using what we call like before and wrap validators

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:13.879
that do something in Python

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:18.520
and then call our internal validation logic

00:16:18.670 --> 00:16:20.020
and then maybe even do something after,

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:20.980
it's okay.

00:16:20.990 --> 00:16:22.700
You can use model validate

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:25.220
and the built-in JSON.loads

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:26.460
because you're already kind of guaranteed

00:16:26.630 --> 00:16:28.760
to be materializing Python objects in that case.

00:16:29.300 --> 00:16:30.520
But for the vast majority of cases,

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:33.320
it's great to just go with the built-in model validate JSON.

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:35.320
Yeah, that's really good advice.

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:37.680
And they seem kind of equivalent,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.460
but once you know the internals, right,

00:16:40.610 --> 00:16:42.260
then it's, well, maybe it's not exactly.

00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:43.080
Yeah.

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:55.260
And I think implementing some of these tips is helpful in that if you understand some of the kind of like Pydantic architectural context, it can also just help you think more about like, how can I write my Pydantic code better?

00:16:57.380 --> 00:16:57.540
Absolutely.

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:09.520
So the next tip I have here, very easy one-liner fix, which is when you're using a type adapter, which is this structure you can use to basically validate one type.

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:14.040
So we have base models, which we've chatted about before,

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:16.740
which is like if you have a model with lots of fields,

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:18.860
that's kind of the structure you use to define it.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.439
Well, type adapter is great if you're like,

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:23.780
I just want to validate that this data is a list of integers,

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:25.480
for example, as we're seeing on the screen.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.500
Right, because let me give people an idea.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:33.300
If you've got a JSON, well, just JSON data from wherever,

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:35.920
but a lot of times it's coming over an API

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:37.340
or it's provided to you as a file

00:17:37.460 --> 00:17:39.460
and it's not your data you control, right?

00:17:39.580 --> 00:17:40.340
you're trying to validate it,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:45.240
you could get a dictionary, a JSON object

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:47.720
that's got curly braces with a bunch of stuff,

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:49.720
in which case that's easy to map to a class.

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:52.200
But if you just have JSON, which is bracket,

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:54.060
thing, thing, thing, thing, close bracket,

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:58.500
well, how do you have a class that represents a list?

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:02.200
It gets really tricky to be able to understand.

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:04.020
You can't model that with classes.

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:06.280
And so you all have this type adapter thing.

00:18:07.220 --> 00:18:09.220
That's what the role plays generally.

00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:09.620
Is that right?

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:10.400
Yeah.

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:13.420
And I think it's also really helpful in a testing context.

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:19.380
Like, you know, when we want to check that our validation behavior is right for one type,

00:18:19.660 --> 00:18:22.040
there's no reason to go like build an entire model.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:27.000
If you're really just validating against one type or structure, type adapter is great.

00:18:28.660 --> 00:18:34.280
And so kind of the advice here is you only want to initialize your type adapter object

00:18:34.580 --> 00:18:34.740
once.

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:43.380
And the reason behind that is we build a core schema in Python and then attach that to a class or type adapter, et cetera.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:57.260
And so if you can, you know, not build that type adapter within your loop, but instead of instead do it right before or not build it, you know, in your function, but instead outside of it, then you can avoid building the core schema over and over again.

00:18:58.100 --> 00:19:02.420
Yeah. So basically what you're saying is that the type adapter that you create

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:08.520
might as well be a singleton because it's stateless, right? Like it doesn't store any data.

00:19:09.300 --> 00:19:14.460
It's kind of slightly expensive to create relatively. And so if you had a function that

00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:17.480
was called over and over again, and that function had a loop and inside the loop,

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:20.820
you're creating the type adapter, that'd be like worst case scenario almost, right?

00:19:21.420 --> 00:19:25.380
Yeah, exactly. And I think this kind of goes along with like general best programming tips,

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:29.920
Right, which is like, if you only need to create something once, do that once.

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:30.500
Exactly.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:30.880
Exactly.

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:37.040
You know, a parallel that maybe goes way, way back in time could be like a compiled regular

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:37.620
expression.

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:40.660
You know, you wouldn't do that over and over in a loop.

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:44.500
You would just create a regular, the compiled regular expression and use it throughout your

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:44.820
program.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:49.840
Right, because it's kind of expensive to do that, but it's fast once it's created.

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:51.280
Yeah, exactly.

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:52.540
And funny that you mentioned that.

00:19:52.700 --> 00:20:00.880
I actually fixed a bug last week where we were compiling regular expressions twice when folks like specified that as a constraint on a field.

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:06.220
So definitely just something to keep in mind and easy to fix or implement with type adapters here.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:10.240
Yeah. Awesome. OK, I like this one. That's a good one.

00:20:10.780 --> 00:20:16.100
Yeah. So this next tip also kind of goes along with like general best practices.

00:20:16.420 --> 00:20:19.680
But the more specific you can be with your type hints, the better.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:26.940
And so specifically, if you know that you have a list of integers, it's better and more efficient

00:20:26.980 --> 00:20:32.340
to specify a type hint as a list of integers instead of a sequence of integers, for example.

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:40.100
Or if you know you have a dictionary that maps strings to integers, specify that type hint as a dictionary, not a mapping.

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:42.620
Interesting.

