Yeah, so you could import sequence from the type in module, which is the generic way.

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:55.140
But I guess you probably have specific code that runs that can validate lists more efficiently

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:57.320
than a general iterable type of thing, right?

00:20:57.860 --> 00:20:58.560
Yeah, exactly.

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:03.940
So in the case of a sequence versus a list, it's the square and rectangle thing, right?

00:21:04.080 --> 00:21:07.260
A list is a sequence, but there are lots of other types of sequences.

00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:11.800
And so you can imagine for a sequence, we have to check lots of other things.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
Whereas if you know with certainty this is going to be a list or it should be a list,

00:21:16.500 --> 00:21:19.760
then you can have things be more efficient with specificity there.

00:21:20.740 --> 00:21:26.500
Does it make any difference at all whether you use the more modern type specifications?

