00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.320
So kind of a more complex performance optimization is using tagged unions.

00:26:01.780 --> 00:26:02.460
They're still pretty simple.

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:05.100
It's just like a little bit more than a one line change.

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:13.040
So kind of talking about tagged unions, we can go through a basic example, why we're using

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:16.100
tagged unions in the first place, and then some more advanced examples.

00:26:16.940 --> 00:26:18.800
And once again, these slides will be posted.

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:22.720
So let's start with what are tagged unions, because I honestly have no idea.

00:26:22.720 --> 00:26:25.320
I know what unions are, but tagging them, I don't know.

00:26:25.880 --> 00:26:32.100
Yeah, sure thing. So tag unions are a special type of union. We also call them discriminated unions.

00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:41.040
And they help you specify a member of a model that you can use for discrimination in your validation.

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:50.720
So what that means is if you have two models that are pretty similar and your field can be either one of those types of models, Model X or Model Y.

00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:56.280
but you know that there's one tag or like discriminator field that differs,

00:26:57.160 --> 00:27:02.640
you can specifically validate against that field and skip some of the other validation, right? So

00:27:02.760 --> 00:27:08.680
like, I'll move on to an example here in a second. But basically, it helps you validate

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:13.280
more efficiently because you get to skip validation of some fields. So it's really

00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:17.299
helpful if you have models that have like 100 fields, but one of them is really indicative of

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:22.980
what type it might be. I see. So instead of trying to figure out like, is it all of this stuff,

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:28.240
once you know it has this aspect or that aspect, then you can sort of branch down a path and just

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:34.540
treat it as one of the elements of the union. Is that right? Yes, exactly. Okay. And so one other

00:27:34.720 --> 00:27:40.220
note about discriminated unions is you specify this discriminator and it can either be a string

00:27:40.760 --> 00:27:45.819
like literal type or callable type. And we'll look at some examples of both. So here's kind of a more

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:52.360
concrete examples so we can really better understand this. So let's say we have a,

00:27:52.620 --> 00:27:55.940
this is the classic example, right? A cat model and a dog model.

00:27:57.440 --> 00:27:59.600
Cat people, dog people, you're going to start a debate here.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:07.540
Exactly, exactly. They both have this pet type field. And for the cat model, it's a literal that

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:12.180
is just the string cat. And then for the dog model, it's the literal that's the string dog.

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:29.720
So it's just kind of a flag on a model to indicate what type it is. And you can imagine, you know, in this basic case, we only have a couple of fields attached to each model, but maybe this is like data in a, like vet database. And so you can imagine like there's going to be tons of fields attached to this, right?

00:28:30.220 --> 00:28:34.680
So it'd be pretty helpful to just be able to look at it and say, oh, the pet type is dog.

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:38.240
Let's make sure this data is valid for a dog type.

00:28:39.220 --> 00:28:40.740
Also note, we have a lizard in here.

00:28:43.800 --> 00:28:51.120
So what this looks like in terms of validation with Pydantic then is that when we specify this pet field,

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:56.960
we just add one extra setting which says that the discriminator is that pet type field.

00:28:58.080 --> 00:29:05.640
And so then when we pass in data that corresponds to a dog model, Pydantic is smart enough to say, oh, this is a discriminated union field.

00:29:05.950 --> 00:29:12.460
Let me go look for the pet type field on the model and just see what that is.

00:29:12.490 --> 00:29:16.640
And then use that to inform my decision for what type I should validate against.

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:18.120
Okay, that's awesome.

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:27.800
So if we don't set the discriminator keyword value in the field for the union, it'll still work, right?

00:29:27.900 --> 00:29:30.720
it just has to be more exhaustive and slow.

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:32.100
Yeah, exactly.

00:29:32.560 --> 00:29:35.300
So it'll still validate and it'll say,

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:36.520
hey, let's take this input data

00:29:36.610 --> 00:29:38.760
and try to validate it against the cat model.

00:29:39.050 --> 00:29:40.440
And then Pydantic will come back and say,

00:29:40.580 --> 00:29:41.580
oh, that's not a valid cat.

00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:42.720
Like, let's try the next one.

00:29:43.520 --> 00:29:45.780
Whereas with this discriminated pattern,

00:29:45.890 --> 00:29:47.060
we can skip right to the dog,

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:50.440
which you can imagine helps us skip some of the-

00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:52.260
Yeah, absolutely.

00:29:52.340 --> 00:29:53.280
Okay, that's really cool.

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:54.860
I had no idea about this.

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:55.240
Yeah, yeah.

00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:58.240
It's a cool, I'd say, moderate-level feature.

00:29:58.740 --> 00:30:00.640
I think if you're just starting to use Pydantic,

00:30:00.730 --> 00:30:03.340
you probably haven't touched discriminated unions much,

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:05.580
but we hope that it's simple enough to implement

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:08.080
that most folks can use it if they're using unions.

00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:09.300
Yeah, that's cool.

00:30:09.570 --> 00:30:11.920
I don't use unions very often, which is probably why,

00:30:12.410 --> 00:30:15.300
other than something PipeNone, which is optional.

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:19.120
But if I did, I'll definitely remember this.

00:30:19.760 --> 00:30:20.020
Yeah.

00:30:21.980 --> 00:30:22.320
All righty.

00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:25.540
So as I've mentioned, this helps for more efficient validation.

00:30:26.570 --> 00:30:33.740
And then where this really comes and has a lot of value is when you are dealing with lots of nested models or models that have tons of fields.

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:38.940
So let's say you have a union with like 10 members and each member of the union has 100 fields.

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:45.840
If you can just do validation against 100 fields instead of 1,000, that would be great in terms of a performance gain.

00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:53.420
And then once again with nested models, you know, if you can skip lots of those union member validations, also going to boost your performance.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:54.780
Yeah, for sure.

00:30:55.180 --> 00:31:06.260
You know, an example where this seems very likely would be using it with Beanie or some other document database where the modeling structure is very hierarchical.

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:11.220
You end up with a lot of nested sub-identic models in there.

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:11.640
Yeah.

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:13.500
Yeah, very much so.

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:14.180
Cool.

00:31:15.220 --> 00:31:24.800
So as a little bit of an added benefit, we can talk about kind of this improved error handling, which is a great way to kind of visualize why the discriminated union pattern is more efficient.

00:31:25.820 --> 00:31:31.820
So right now we're looking at an example of validation against a model that doesn't use a discriminated union.

00:31:32.620 --> 00:31:34.860
And the errors are not very nice to look at.

00:31:35.390 --> 00:31:40.900
You basically see the errors for every single permutation of the different values.

00:31:41.050 --> 00:31:44.120
And we're using nested models, so it's very hard to interpret.

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:50.260
it. So we don't have to look at this for too long. It's not very nice. But if we look at...

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:55.160
But basically, the error message says, look, there's something wrong with the union. If it

00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:59.800
was a string, it is missing these things. If it was this kind of thing, it misses those things.

00:32:00.020 --> 00:32:05.960
If it was a dog, it misses this. If it's a cat, it misses that. And it doesn't specifically tell

00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:11.760
you. It's a dog, so it's missing the collar size or whatever, right?

00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:31.960
Right, exactly. But then, and I'll go back and kind of explain the discriminated model for this case in a second. But if you look at this is the model with the discriminated union instead, we have one very nice error that says, okay, you're trying to, you know, validate this X field and it's the wrong type, right?

