00:49:40.960 --> 00:49:43.080
It's just not as easy as like there's a text field

00:49:43.120 --> 00:49:44.160
I paste in my stuff,

00:49:44.720 --> 00:49:48.080
but it does technically work, I suppose.

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:49.240
Yeah.

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:51.400
But no, definitely the LLM approach

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:53.180
or just the basic website approaches

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:54.480
are very quick, which is nice.

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:55.780
Yeah.

00:49:55.980 --> 00:49:57.280
Speaking of LLMs, just really quick.

00:49:57.440 --> 00:50:04.260
I feel you get some of the Python newsletters and other places, like, here's the cool new packages.

00:50:04.510 --> 00:50:08.320
A lot of them are like, nine out of 10 of them are about LLMs these days.

00:50:08.390 --> 00:50:10.240
I was like, that feels a little over the top to me.

00:50:10.420 --> 00:50:12.560
But I know there's other things going on in the world.

00:50:13.240 --> 00:50:16.500
But just put your thoughts on LLMs and encoding these days.

00:50:16.590 --> 00:50:22.020
I know you write a lot of code and think about it a lot and probably use LLMs somewhere in there.

00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:23.640
Yeah, no, for sure.

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:27.140
I'm pretty optimistic and excited about it.

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:38.960
I think there's a lot of good that can be done and a lot of productivity boosting to be had from integrating with these tools, both in your local development environment and also just in general.

00:50:39.870 --> 00:50:42.940
I think sometimes it's also great in the performance department, right?

00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:50.880
Like we can see with CodeFlash, using LLMs to help you write more performant code can also be really useful.

00:50:51.280 --> 00:51:08.520
And it's been exciting to see some libraries really leverage Pydantic as well in that space in terms of like validating LLM outputs or even using LLM calls in Pydantic validators to validate, you know, data along constraints that are more like language model friendly.

00:51:10.260 --> 00:51:11.760
So, yeah, I'm optimistic about it.

00:51:11.760 --> 00:51:18.680
I still have a lot to learn, but it's cool to see the variety of applications and kind of where you can plug in Pydantic in that process for fun.

00:51:18.800 --> 00:51:20.020
Yeah, I totally agree.

00:51:20.820 --> 00:51:26.140
Right now, the context window, how much you can give it as information

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:28.740
then to start asking questions is still a little bit small.

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:31.960
You can't give it some huge program and say,

00:51:32.710 --> 00:51:35.040
find me the bugs where this function is called, or whatever.

00:51:35.070 --> 00:51:37.740
And it doesn't quite understand enough all at once,

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:40.420
but that thing keeps growing.

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:42.380
So eventually, someday, we'll all see.

00:51:43.260 --> 00:51:43.520
Yep.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:45.440
All right.

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:56.980
Well, let's talk just for a minute, maybe real quick about what you all are doing at Pydantic, the company, rather than Pydantic, the open source library.

00:51:57.200 --> 00:51:58.400
Like what do you all got going on there?

00:51:59.440 --> 00:51:59.940
Yeah, sure.

00:52:00.240 --> 00:52:06.120
So Pydantic has, the company has released our first commercial tool.

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:08.940
It's called Logfire and it's in open beta.

00:52:09.710 --> 00:52:11.260
So it's an observability platform.

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:15.760
And we would really encourage anyone interested to try it out.

00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:23.280
It's super easy to get started with, you know, just the basic like pip install of the SDK and then start using it in your code base.

00:52:23.780 --> 00:52:30.280
And then we have the kind of Logfire dashboard where you're going to see the observability and results.

00:52:30.860 --> 00:52:42.660
And so we kind of adopt this like needle in the haystack philosophy, where we want this to be a very easy to use observability platform that offers very like Python centric insights.

00:52:44.080 --> 00:52:50.320
And it's this kind of opinionated wrapper around open telemetry, if folks are familiar with that.

00:52:51.640 --> 00:53:00.480
But in kind of the context of performance, one of the great things about this tool is that it offers this like nested logging and profiling structure for code.

00:53:01.700 --> 00:53:03.360
and so it can be really helpful in

00:53:04.240 --> 00:53:05.540
kind of looking at your code and being like

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:07.400
we don't know where this performance

00:53:07.660 --> 00:53:09.480
slowdown is occurring but if we

00:53:09.660 --> 00:53:11.440
integrate with Logfire we can see that like very

00:53:11.700 --> 00:53:12.960
easily in the dashboard

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:15.680
Yeah you also

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:17.680
yeah you have some interesting

00:53:17.940 --> 00:53:19.660
approaches like specifically targeting

00:53:20.440 --> 00:53:21.440
popular frameworks like

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:23.780
Instrument FastAPI

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:25.340
or something like that right?

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:27.760
Yeah definitely trying to

00:53:27.920 --> 00:53:29.418
kind of build integrations that

00:53:29.440 --> 00:53:35.660
work very well with FastAPI, other tools like that. And even also offering kind of like custom

00:53:36.840 --> 00:53:40.880
features in the dashboard, right? Like if you're looking at, you know, if you're using an observability

00:53:41.080 --> 00:53:44.800
tool, you're probably advanced enough to want to add some extra things to your dashboard. And

00:53:44.990 --> 00:53:49.260
we're working on supporting that with FastUI, which I know you've chatted with Samuel about as well.

00:53:49.880 --> 00:53:55.418
Yeah, absolutely. I got a chance to talk to Samuel about Logfire and some of the

00:53:55.640 --> 00:53:57.600
behind the scenes infrastructure was really interesting.

00:53:57.750 --> 00:54:01.820
But also speaking of Fast UI, you know, I did speak to him.

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:02.360
When was that?

00:54:03.090 --> 00:54:03.600
Back in February.

00:54:04.470 --> 00:54:07.040
So this is a really popular project.

00:54:07.150 --> 00:54:14.400
And even on the, I was like, quite a few people decided that they were interested in even watching

00:54:14.430 --> 00:54:17.460
the video on that one, which, yeah.

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:19.140
Anything with Fast UI?

00:54:22.360 --> 00:54:23.960
Sorry, did you say anything with Fast UI?

00:54:25.360 --> 00:54:31.480
yeah yeah are you doing anything on the fast UI side are you on the pydantic uh side of things

00:54:32.380 --> 00:54:37.300
yeah good question i've been working mostly on pydantic uh just you know larger user base

00:54:37.700 --> 00:54:42.420
more feature requests but excited to um i've done a little bit on the fast UI side and excited to

00:54:42.640 --> 00:54:47.160
kind of brush up on my type script and build that out as a more robust and supported tool

00:54:47.760 --> 00:54:52.258
i think especially as we grow as a company and have more open source support in general that'll

00:54:52.280 --> 00:54:54.080
be a priority for us, which is exciting.

00:54:54.520 --> 00:54:54.860
Yeah.

00:54:56.760 --> 00:54:57.780
It's an interesting project.

00:54:58.100 --> 00:55:03.320
Basically, a cool way to do JavaScript front-ends and React

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:06.980
and then plug those back into Python APIs,

00:55:07.360 --> 00:55:09.980
like FastAPI and those types of things, right?

00:55:10.220 --> 00:55:10.940
So, yeah.

